reviewText: You know there are plenty of people who are hard of hearing.Does Hollywood not care about that? Is it so frickin' expensive to provide subtitles? After all, with the soundtrack blasting and the FX explosions and whatnot and the sound designers not worrying ab out dialogue anymore, you need subtitles to understand what is going on.Or iis it that there is not point because the plot is so stupid anyway?

reviewText: I'm not going to talk about the low budget aspect that others have mentioned, except for the fact that for under $25K they did a heroic job. No my problem is with the story, specifically that we're supposed to believe that such an unprofessional bunch would be sent to save humanity. The infighting at the beginning of the movie between the humans is unbelievable. Have the writers not ever met someone in the military? I don't mean your average first year boot, I mean professionals with experience who would probably be selected to undertake this task. There would be no fighting, there would simply be the mission, and the dedication and commitment to complete it by a group skilled enough to accomplish it.

reviewText: This movie was unbelievably stupid.  I expected to see our spaceships fighting alien invaders in alien spaceships.  There were none.  I expected to see aliens.  There were no alien beings.The movie consisted of the crew (4 or 5 people) on another planet, walking around, and talking.  They were trying to decide what to do.  Their mission was to go to this planet and spread a virus that would kill everyone on the planet.The so-called aliens on this planet looked like human beings -- not aliens. There were 3 of them. That's all. The first "alien" was wearing some sort of white suit that had pieces of cloth hanging off of it and a funny looking mask.  It reminded me of a bunny suit.  When I first saw it, I started to laugh.  It was very funny.  After that point, I just "fast-forwarded" through the movie until the very end.It ended with the crew throwing the container of virus toward a structure that was black in color but you couldn't make out what exactly it was.The End.
summary: No Spaceships  -- No Aliens -- Totally Stupid

reviewText: You need to go into this movie knowing what you're getting.  It's low-budget, so don't expect the light saber fight or phaser battle amongst some rocks or something.  Dearth of money = dearth of things worth filming.  That means you had better be left with a good story.  Sadly this wasn't the case here.  Yes, there is some suspense.  Yes, some of you may be compelled (as I was) to make it to the ending, just to figure out what the hell was going on for most of the movie.  Yes, there was some potential for a moment.  What you get instead is a lot of smoke and mirrors--so-and-so might be an alien, or he might not be, blah-blah-blah.  Forty minutes later:  we should kill him--no we shouldn't--yes, we should, blah-blah--what kind of people are we--blah-blah some more...... (uh-oh, 10 minutes left) time for the big reveal, such as it is.  You can write better stories than this just from listening to conversations in a mall.  The characters are not very believable either.  My biggest hang-ups were the doc:  since when is a civilian allowed to bark orders on a military mission?  and Lieutenant Gray:  a real officer would never second guess himself in front of his subordinates....that and he just sounds weaselly.  No real chain of command, no real sense of order, therefore no real sense of authenticity.

reviewText: This feels more like an extended episode of the New Outer Limits which is why it appealed to me. The story is not bad after you get about 1/3 the way into the film. I really think it has more potential to be a remake with a bigger budget; however, a sequel with a bigger budget would be just as cool. Overall I recommend it for low-budget B-movie fans without hesitation.
